// COMPILE_FAIL: == on multi-field custom struct (silent miscompile guard, S104-B)
//
// Before S104-B, equality on a multi-field aggregate fell through to
// emit_binop_typed's extract-first-field branch, which silently
// extracted only the first field and compared it. For `Point { x, y }`
// that meant `Point { x: 1, y: 2 } == Point { x: 1, y: 99 }` returned
// `true` because only `x` was inspected — a silent miscompile.
//
// S104-B turns this into a hard codegen error. The S98–S103 dispatch
// chain handles every known eq-family aggregate (str / String / &String
// / & &String / &[T] / Vec<T> / &Vec<T>) by routing through @str_eq.
// Any other aggregate (custom struct, Option/Result, fat-ref of custom
// type, closure, HashMap) reaches the default path and now diagnoses
// instead of miscompiling.
//
// Workarounds for legitimate use cases:
//   - custom struct: `#[derive(PartialEq)]` and call `.eq()`
//   - Option/Result: pattern-match
//   - HashMap: not supported (architectural; needs iteration)
//   - closure: not comparable
//
// EXPECT: equality on multi-field aggregate type
mod std;

struct Point {
    x: i32,
    y: i32,
}

fn main() -> i32 {
    let p1 = Point { x: 1, y: 2 };
    let p2 = Point { x: 1, y: 99 };
    if p1 == p2 { 0 } else { 1 }
}
